******
[1] South America (multicountry)
Date: Tue 6 Feb 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: BBC News - UK [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/6335819.stm>


A health alert has been declared in Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia
after an outbreak of dengue fever. The authorities have blamed higher
rainfall this season as a cause of the unusually rapid spread of the
disease. Experts also say the uncommonly warm weather has boosted the
population of mosquitoes, which transmit the disease.

Dengue fever is not uncommon in South America, where thousands of
cases are recorded every year. The difference this time is the speed
with which the disease has spread across the south of the continent.

Brazil, Paraguay, Bolivia and, to a lesser extent, Argentina have
been affected by the outbreak - but it is Brazil and Paraguay which
have seen the worst of it.

Fatalities
------------------
In the southwestern Brazilian state of Mato Grosso do Sul it is
estimated that more than 15 000 people have been infected this year
[2007] -- more than all the cases registered in 2006.

In Paraguay there have been more than 3000 cases and 4 people have
already died. In Bolivia, a young nurse died last week [week of 28
Jan 2007].

The authorities have called on the population to take more preventive
measures to avoid infection. In the meantime, the authorities in
Brazil, Bolivia, and Paraguay have declared a health alert and
increased measures to try to stop the outbreak from escalating into a
fully blown regional epidemic.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

