[2] Peru (La Libertad, Lambayeque)
Date: Fri 9 Feb 2007
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: China View [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-02/09/content_5718446.htm>


A 2nd person has died of dengue since the outbreak of the disease in
the north of Peru, the Health Ministry said on Thursday [8 Feb 2007].

A man died in the Trujillo Regional Hospital, in the province of La
Libertad, 550 km. North of Peru's capital, Lima, after suffering high
fever, hemorrhage and pain all over her body.

Another 133 cases of dengue fever have been detected by the Regional
Health Directorate (DRS) in the El Porvenir district [of La Libertad
] province, where the victim has been living.

The 1st victim, a 79-year-old man, who died last week [week of 28 Jan
2007], was also a resident of La Libertad.

The ministry said it started anti-mosquito spraying in a bid to stamp
out the mosquito by clearing out stagnant water where it breeds.

The DRS has identified 4525 homes, which are at risk from the
mosquito that spreads dengue, and has declared a state of health
emergency in the region.

Another 16 cases were found this year [2007] in the neighboring
province of Lambayeque, some 200 km. distant, the Ministry said,
adding that there was a 150-case outbreak of dengue in the province
last year.

The Ministry examined dengue samples sent to the [capital] and said
there have been no cases of hemorrhagic dengue in Lambayeque.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report from China View has conflicting information with one
found in Spanish from the AP 9 Feb 2007
<http://espanol.news.yahoo.com/s/ap/070210/salud/ams_med_peru_dengue>
which mentions 398 cases in the whole country, 193 of which occurred
in La Libertad province (China View says 133 in one district of the
same province.) The information regarding the 2 fatal cases is also
different. However, this AP report doesn't say anything about the
cases in the Lambayeque province. - Copy Ed.MJ]

[It would be interesting to know if the dengue virus serotype
circulating in Peru is DENV-3 and related to that serotype virus
being transmitted in other parts of South America.

