[4] Chile (Easter Island)
Date: Mon 12 Feb 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Mostrador, Chile, [edited; trans. Mod.TY]
<http://www.elmostrador.cl/modulos/noticias/constructor/noticia_new.asp?id_noticia=209842>


Health authorities confirmed that 3 dengue cases have been detected
on Easter Island [Isla de Pascua in Spanish], and have put into
action measures to eradicate the outbreak.

In a press release in Valparaiso, the Undersecretary of Health, Lidia
Amarales, said on Saturday [10 Feb 2007] that the affected
individuals are 2 men ages 33 and 46 years, and a woman of 27 years,
all of who are undergoing treatment on the island. In addition, there
are 2 other individuals with febrile disease compatible with dengue
fever, said Amarales.

She added that the cases were confirmed as having been infected with
dengue 1 [virus], its most benign form. [Although these 3 confirmed
and 2 suspected cases may not be especially severe, none of the 4
dengue virus serotypes can be classified as uniformly "benign". -
Mod.TY]

Dengue [fever], termed "nao nao" in the [local] Rapa Nui language,
was 1st detected on Easter Island in 2000, but the most serious
outbreak was in 2002, when 600 cases were reported on this small
Pacific island.

Currently, the island is celebrating the traditional "Tapati"
festival with the usual population of 4000 inhabitants practically
doubling for 2 weeks.

Undersecretary Amarales called on the local residents and tourists to
undertake measures to avoid proliferation of the mosquito vector
_Aedes aegypti_. She explained that trash and other recipients in
which water could accumulate and serve as breeding sites should be
eliminated, and bed nets and insect repellents sent from the mainland
should be used. [Elimination of breeding sites is very important.
Because _Ae. aegypti_ are day-biting mosquitoes, bed nets may not be
particularly useful to avoid transmission. - Mod.TY]

The Minister of Health confirmed this Sunday [11 Feb 2007] that a
team of professionals will be sent to the island, under the
supervision of the Regional Secretary [of Health], Nestor Irribarra,
which will deal with this emergency.

The team, with help of navy personnel, will fumigate the entire
island starting Monday [12 Feb 2007], starting with the town of Hanga
Roa and vicinity, action focused on [the areas] of the [dengue fever]
cases. Also, aircraft going between the island and the Chilean
mainland will be fumigated to avoid [mosquito] transport of the
[virus] to Chile, which has been free of the disease.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Avoiding inadvertent transport of infected mosquitoes to the Chilean
mainland is prudent, but it would be more difficult to avoid
transport of infected individuals incubating dengue virus infection,
especially tourists and visitors for the "Tapati" festival. We wish
the Chilean health authorities success in controlling the outbreak
and congratulate them for their prompt and vigorous response to the
situation.

A map of Easter Island can be accessed at:
<http://www.osdpd.noaa.gov/PSB/EPS/icg/EASTER.gif>. - Mod.TY]

